  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "The appropriate use of \"Ms.\", \"Mrs.\", and \"Miss\" typically depends on the woman's marital status and preference:\n\n1. **Ms.**: This is a neutral title that can be used for any adult woman, regardless of her marital status. It is the most versatile and modern form of address and is often preferred when the marital status is unknown or when the woman prefers not to reveal it.\n\n2. **Mrs.**: This title is traditionally used for women who are married. It is appropriate when you know a woman is married and she prefers to be addressed this way. It is also used in conjunction with the husband's name, such as \"Mrs. John Smith\", though modern usage may favor the woman's own first name, like \"Mrs. Jane Smith\".\n\n3. **Miss**: This title is used for unmarried women or girls. It is seen as more old-fashioned and less commonly used for adult women today compared to \"Ms.\". It may still be used for young girls or when the woman expresses a preference for this title.\n\n**Tips for choosing the appropriate title:**\n- When in doubt, \"Ms.\" is a safe and respectful choice.\n- Pay attention to how a woman introduces herself or signs her name, as this can give a clue to her preferred title.\n- If you're addressing someone formally in written communication (e.g., a business letter), \"Ms.\" is typically suitable unless you have specific information about her marital status and her title preference.\n\nRemember, it\u2019s always courteous to ask a woman her preferred title if you\u2019re unsure and circumstances allow.",
